LAZY REVIEW:
YESTERDAY works primarily because The Beatles is so iconic, it turns even the silliest plots into gold. The story follows a struggling musician named Jack Malik, who wakes up after being hit by a bus learning that the world has no memory of the greatest band of all time. He then sings their songs and become famous, at the expense of the love of his life. Himesh Patel, who plays Jack Malik, is great at covering The Beatles, and I really felt the pain of going to choose between his priorities. There was a scene where he sang â€œHelp!â€ in front of a cheering crowd and he was literally screaming help because he wanted to get out of his situation. That part really struck a chord. But what really draws me to the story is the magnetic charm of Lily James. I loved her as Debra in Baby Driver and here sheâ€™s just oozing with charisma that any guy would fall in love with her character. Ed Sheeranâ€™s inclusion in the movie gave the story the necessary foundation to elevate Jack Malikâ€™s rise to fame, while showing heâ€™s definitely one of the best musical composers of this generation. SNLâ€™s Kate McKinnon, always over-the-top with her performances, affirms that this tale is indeed a comedy. I was disappointed that all of Ana De Armasâ€™ scenes were cut in the film, as mentioned by director Danny Boyle, she was too good in it that it complicated the love story between Jack and Elly. Such a waste. YESTERDAY may not be a perfect movie, but it definitely lands in the â€œfeel-goodâ€ movie category. If you're a big fan of The Beatles (like me) then you shouldn't miss this, specially the surprise towards the end. yesterdaymovie
